 *1315789836*Photo Reading 5 Day Test Summary
 <a href='http://d.hatena.ne.jp/nishiohirokazu/20110907/1315358107'>Try the 5-day photo reading test</a>, <a href='http://d.hatena.ne.jp/ nishiohirokazu/20110908/1315442582'>Part 2</a>, <a href='http://d.hatena.ne.jp/nishiohirokazu/20110909/1315530110'>Photo Reading 5 Day Test Part 3</ This is the final part following <a href=''>PhotoReading 5-Day Test Part 3</a>. After all, it's a 5-day test, but I've done it in 4 days.
 
 Let's start with the objective. I read the book ("Beyond Freud", hardcover, 191 pages), which I had bought but left piled up, in four days at 25 minutes a day, and blogged its contents. <a href='http://d.hatena.ne.jp/nishiohirokazu/20110912/1315788897'>'Beyond Freud' Leverage Memo</a>
 
 Thoughts. A stack of books does not create value. I don't think I absorbed 100% of what was written in the book, but I think I absorbed the important parts. How much I absorbed cannot be objectively measured, and there is no way for me to measure it. I would like someone in the know to tell me whether I learned more or less in less than two hours. Well, at least it's a good thing that the "paper trash piled up in my room" has turned into "knowledge in my brain". I still have a lot of books to read, so I will continue to process them in this way.
 
 I had a preconceived notion of Freud as a "dirty old man who links everything to sexuality," but now that I understand why he tried to link all human behavior to sexual desire, I have a lot of sympathy for him. It's more like sympathy... If only he had been born in an age when brain waves could be measured or experiments could be done with monkeys, his ideals would have been easier to achieve.
 
